"* [IO]Stdin (src/runtime/io.rs + qnlib/core/06-io.qn) — the readable standard stream.
"*
"* Only the cases that need NO input live here: a test running under `qn test` inherits the
"* harness's stdin, so actually reading would consume it (or block on a terminal). Everything
"* that needs a controlled pipe or a file redirect is in `tests/io_stdin.rs`.
"*
"* Design notes worth keeping in view:
"*  - `[IO]Stdin` is a CLASS, not a constant like [IO]Stdout / [IO]Stderr. Opening stdin parks
"*    on the scheduler, and the prelude also runs under `qn benchmark`, which has none — so the
"*    stream is created on the first read, not at startup.
"*  - Reads park the task; a program can serve sockets while it waits on a line.
"*  - The stream is memoized, because a stream buffers: two streams over fd 0 would each hold
"*    bytes the other never sees.

(TestSuite.new:{ var name = 'IOStdin' }).add:{
    "* A namespace class (see 54-native-new.qn) — the stream lives behind `.stream`.
    .test:isANamespaceClass -> {
        .does:{ [IO]Stdin.new } throw:#/Cannot instantiate abstract class/
    };

    "* These are class-side methods, so `can?:` must be asked of the metaclass — on a Class
    "* receiver it reports *instance* methods (see 17-can.qn).
    .test:respondsToTheReadingProtocol -> {
        .isTrue:{ [IO]Stdin.meta.can?:#readLine };
        .isTrue:{ [IO]Stdin.meta.can?:#eachLine: };
        .isTrue:{ [IO]Stdin.meta.can?:#readAll };
        .isTrue:{ [IO]Stdin.meta.can?:#stream };
        .isTrue:{ [IO]Stdin.meta.can?:#byteStream }
    };

    "* stdout/stderr are write-only: refused where the mistake is made, not at the first read.
    .test:theWriteHandlesRefuseToBeRead -> {
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stdout).stringStream } throw:IoError;
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stderr).stringStream } throw:IoError;
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stdout).stringStream } throw:#/only stdin is readable/;
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stderr).byteStream } throw:#/write-only/
    };

    "* Conversely, stdin is not a sink. A typed IoError, not a bare String — `catch:{|e:Error|}`
    "* must be able to see it.
    .test:stdinRefusesToBeWritten -> {
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stdin).write:'x' } throw:IoError;
        .does:{ ([IO]Handle.stdin).writeln:'x' } throw:#/read-only/
    }
}
